aumont Charlton-Pollard). Thursday Night Lights tells the inspiring, largely unknown story of African American high school football in Texas. Drawing on interviews, newspaper stories, and memorabilia, Michael Hurd introduces the players, coaches, schools, and towns where African Americans built powerhouse football programs under the PVIL leadership. He covers fifty years (1920–1970) of high school football history, including championship seasons and legendary rivalries such as the annual Turkey Day Classic game between Houston schools Jack Yates and Phillis Wheatley, which drew standing-room-only crowds of up to 40,000, making it the largest prep sports event in postwar America. In telling this story, Hurd explains why the PVIL was necessary, traces its development, and shows how football offered a potent source of pride and ambition in the black community, helping black kids succeed both athletically and educationally in a racist society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aAfrican American football coacheszTexasxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican American football coaches-Texas-History-20th century. 0aAfrican American football playerszTexasxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican American football players-Texas-History-20th century. 0aAfrican American high school studentszTexasxHistoryy20th century. 0aDiscrimination in sportszTexasxHistoryy20th century. 0aDiscrimination in sports-Texas-History-20th century. 0aFootballzTexasxHistoryy20th century. 0aFootball-Texas-History-20th century. 0aPrairie View Interscholastic League (Tex.). 0aSchool sportszTexasxHistoryy20th century. 0aSchool sports-Texas-History-20th century. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311074529040uhttps://doi.org